            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "OK -- this may be my bad -- turns out it was my code, in a pyd file:\r\n\r\n```\r\nfrom libc.stdio cimport FILE\r\nIF UNAME_SYSNAME == \"Windows\":\r\n    cdef extern from \"<windows.h>\":\r\n        ctypedef Py_UNICODE wchar_t\r\n        FILE *_wfopen(const wchar_t *filename,const wchar_t *mode)\r\n```\r\n\r\nSo I explicitly used Py_UNICODE (and only on Windows) -- which I think is then putting PyUnicode_AsUnicode in the generated C code. (maybe -- still can't test on Windows.\r\n\r\nThe question is -- what do I use to pass a filename as a wchar_t ? \r\n\r\n(I wrote that code a long time ago -- it will take a while to refresh my brain on it ...hints welcome)\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n",
